revision.text:
'''Saints Antonina and Alexander''' were [[Christianity|Christian]] [[martyr]]s of 313, and they are [[saint]]s whose ''acta'' are legendary. The story of the two is nearly identical to that of [[Saints Theodora and Didymus]].
[[Diocletian]], in order to increase the number of native-born [[ancient Rome|Roman]] citizens, defined as crime intentional [[celibacy]] among women. All Roman women of suitable age were commanded to marry and, if possible, produce children. At the same time, Diocletian persecuted Christians. The legend of Antonina and Alexander has the former being forced to a [[brothel]] (the penalty for women who refused to wed), where a Christian soldier named Alexander came to her in the guise of a customer. Instead of deflowering her, he traded clothes with her, allowing Antonina to escape. Alexander was discovered very soon after, and both Antonina and Alexander were executed by being burned alive.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Martyrologium Romanum|publisher = Gregory XIII, Pope|year = 1914|isbn = 9781497350298|page = 127|trans-title = The Roman Martyrology|chapter = Quarto die Maii|trans-chapter = The Fourth Day of May|orig-year = 1749}}</ref>
"Antonina" and "Alexander" may be mnemonic device names that made oral repetition of the tale easier, and so it is possible, if not likely, that they are invented names. Whether Theodora and Didymus were the originals or not, it is possible that these legends are shadows of an actual martyrdom that had been lost to the story tellers. The [[feast day]] of Antonina and Alexander in the [[Roman Catholic Church]] is May 3.
