{{Infobox museum | name = Arslan Eyce Private Amphora Museum | native_name = Arslan Eyce Özel Amphora Müzesi | native_name_lang = [[Turkish language|Turkish]] | image = Arslan Eyce Özel Amphora Müzesi.jpg | image_upright = | alt = | caption = Entrance of the museum. | map_type = Turkey | map_relief = | map_size = | map_caption = Location of the Amhora Museum in Turkey. | map_dot_label = | coordinates = {{coord|36|19|03|N|33|52|40|E}} | former_name = | established = {{start date and age|2003}} | location = İsmet Inonu Cad. 62/B, [[Tasucu]], [[Silifke|Silifke, Mersin]], Turkey | type = [[Archaeology]] | accreditation = | key_holdings = | collections = [[Amphora]] | collection_size = 400 | visitors = | founder = Arslan Eyce | director = | president = | chairperson = | curator = | historian = | owner = [[Ministry of Culture and Tourism (Turkey)|Ministry of Culture and Tourism]] | publictransit = | car_park = | parking = | network = | website = [http://www.tasucuamphoramuzesi.com/tr/t-c-kultur-ve-turizm-bakanligi-arslan-eyce-ozel-amphora-muzesi-1997/ Museum page] | embedded = }}
'''Arslan Eyce Private Amphora Museum''', also known as '''Taşucu Amphora Museum''', ({{lang-tr|Arslan Eyce Özel Amphora Müzesi}}) is a [[maritime archaeology]] museum dedicated to [[amphora]] in [[Taşucu]], southern Turkey.
Taşucu, known as Holmi in the antiquity, at {{coord|36|19|03|N|33|52|40|E}} is a seaside town in [[Silifke]] İlçe (district) of [[Mersin Province]]. Formerly, it was an important port. The museum is located in an 18th-century building on the İsmet İnönü Boulevard, which was originally a storage building. The building now is a property of the museum foundation. Arslan Eyce, a citizen of Silifke, spent 40 years in collecting ancient amphorae mostly from shipwrecks. In 1997, the [[Ministry of Culture and Tourism (Turkey)]] took over the collection. After maintenance, the museum was officially opened in 2003.<ref name="TU">[http://www.tasucuamphoramuzesi.com/tr/tasucu-arslan-eyce-amphora-muzesi/ Museum page {{tr icon}}]</ref><ref name="tam"/>
There are 400 amphorae in the museum. The exhibited amphorae span a long time from 3200 BC to 1800 AD.<ref name="TU"/><ref name="tam"/>
[[File:Amphora in Taşucu Amphora Museum.jpg|thumb|upright|left|An amphora in the museum.]]
