[[File:Ectomycorrhiza illustration.jpg|thumb|Hartig net]] '''Hartig net''' is a [[Hyphae|hyphal]] network, that extends into the [[root]], penetrating between the epidermal and cortical [[Cell (biology)|cell]]s of [[ectomycorrhiza]]l plants. This network is a site of nutrient exchange between the [[fungus]] and the host [[plant]].<ref>Carlile, M.J. & Watkinson, S.C. (1994) ''The Fungi.'' Academic Press Ltd, London. pp 329 - 340.</ref>
The Hartig net is named after [[Theodor Hartig]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Money |first1=Nicholas P |title=Mushroom |date=2011 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |page=71}}</ref> <ref>{{cite book |last1=Maser |first1=C |last2=Claridge |first2=A W |last3=Trappe |first3=J M |title=Trees, Truffles, and Beasts: How Forests Function |date=2008 |publisher=Rutgers University Press |location=New Brunswick |page=54}}</ref> , a 19th-century German forest biologist and botanist. He reported research in 1842 on the [[anatomy]] of the interface between ectomycorrhizal fungi and tree roots.
